						<div id=3D"siteSub" class=3D"noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encycl=
opedia</div>
					</div>
					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Mea=
sure of the performance of passers in gridiron football</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Not to be co=
nfused with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Total_quarterback_rati=
ng" title=3D"Total quarterback rating">total quarterback rating</a>.</div>
<p>=20
<b>Passer rating</b> (also known as <b>passing efficiency</b> in college fo=
otball) is a measure of the performance of passers, primarily <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quarterback" title=3D"Quarterback">quarterbacks=
</a>, in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gridiron_football" title=
=3D"Gridiron football">gridiron football</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NFLQBRatin=
g_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Passer_=
rating#cite_note-NFLQBRating-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> There are two formulas currently=
 in use: one used by both the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nati=
onal_Football_League" title=3D"National Football League">National Football =
League</a> (NFL) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canadian_Foot=
ball_League" title=3D"Canadian Football League">Canadian Football League</a=
> (CFL), and the other used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NCA=
A_football" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"NCAA football">NCAA football</a>=
. Passer rating is calculated using a player's passing attempts, completion=
s, yards, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Touchdown" title=3D"Touc=
hdown">touchdowns</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interce=
ption" title=3D"Interception">interceptions</a>. Passer rating in the NFL i=
s on a scale from 0 to 158.3. Passing efficiency in college football is on =
a scale from =E2=88=92731.6 to 1261.6.
</p><p>Since 1973, passer rating has been the official formula used by the =
NFL to determine its passing leader.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-b_2-0" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Passer_rating#cite_note-b-=
2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p><p>Passer rating is sometimes colloquially referred to as <i>quarterbac=
k rating</i> or <i>QB rating</i>; however, the statistic applies only to pa=
ssing (not to other contributions by a quarterback) and applies to any play=
er at any position who throws a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fo=
rward_pass" title=3D"Forward pass">forward pass</a>, not just to quarterbac=
ks. Other measurements, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ES=
PN" title=3D"ESPN">ESPN</a>'s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tota=
l_quarterback_rating" title=3D"Total quarterback rating">total quarterback =
rating</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pro_Football_Focus"=
 title=3D"Pro Football Focus">Pro Football Focus</a> grades have been produ=
ced to take account for non-passing contributions or mistakes made by passe=
rs.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPasser_rating&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Before the development of the passer rating, the NFL struggled with how =
to crown a passing leader.
</p><p>From 1932 to 1937, it was the quarterback with the most passing yard=
age, and from 1938 to 1940, it was the quarterback with the highest complet=
ion percentage. In 1941, a system was created that ranked the league's quar=
terbacks relative to their peers' performance. Over the next thirty years, =
the criteria used to crown a passing leader changed several times, however,=
 the ranking system made it impossible to determine a quarterback's rank un=
til all  quarterbacks had completed their games that week, or to compare qu=
arterback performances across multiple seasons.
</p><p>With this in mind, in 1971, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/NFL_commissioner" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"NFL commissioner">NFL com=
missioner</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pete_Rozelle" title=
=3D"Pete Rozelle">Pete Rozelle</a> asked the league's statistical committee=
 to develop a better system:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-a_3-0" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Passer_rating#cite_note-a-3"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> this committee was headed by Don Smith of the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Pro_Football_Hall_of_Fame" title=3D"Pro Football Hall of =
Fame">Pro Football Hall of Fame</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Seymour_Siwoff" title=3D"Seymour Siwoff">Seymour Siwoff</a> of the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elias_Sports_Bureau" title=3D"Elias Spo=
rts Bureau">Elias Sports Bureau</a>, and NFL executive Don Weiss. Smith and=
 Siwoff established passing performance standards based on data from all qu=
alified pro football passers between 1960 and 1970, and used those data to =
create the passer rating, with the formula being adopted by the NFL in 1973=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-b_2-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Passer_rating#cite_note-b-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"NFL_and_CFL_formula">NFL an=
d CFL formula</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DPasser_rating&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: =
NFL and CFL formula"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The NFL passer rating formula includes five variables: pass attempts, co=
mpletions, passing yards, touchdown passes, and interceptions. Each of thos=
e variables is scaled to a value between 0 and 2.375, with 1.0 being statis=
tically average (based on league data between 1960 and 1970). When the form=
ula was first created, a 66.7 rating indicated an average performance, and =
a 100+ rating indicated an excellent performance.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-a_3-1"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Passer_rating=
#cite_note-a-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> However, passing performance has improved steadi=
ly since then and in 2017 the league average rating was 88.6,<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Passe=
r_rating#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and by 2020 it was 93.6.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Passer_ra=
ting#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The four separate calculations can be expressed in the following equ=
ations:
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=
