<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Total_quarterback_rating">T=
otal quarterback rating</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DPasser_rating&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit =
section: Total quarterback rating"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Total_quarterback_ra=
ting" title=3D"Total quarterback rating">Total quarterback rating</a></div>
<p>ESPN's total quarterback rating is a proprietary statistic that was intr=
oduced in 2011 and is designed to measure the total effectiveness and perfo=
rmance of a quarterback. The metric takes into account all of a quarterback=
's contribution to a game, including passing, rushing, sacks, penalties, to=
uchdowns, and turnovers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_12-0" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Passer_rating#cite_note-:1-12"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> Moreover, each play is weighted based on its "difficulty", the conte=
xt of the game, and the strength of the opposing defense. This means that s=
tatistics in garbage time of a blowout game hold less merit than statistics=
 in a close game. Also, a quarterback who throws for four touchdowns and 30=
0 yards against a strong defense will have a higher QBR than a quarterback =
who has the same stat line against the worst defense in the NFL.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-:1_12-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Passer_rating#cite_note-:1-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>QBR functions on a 0=E2=80=93100 scale, where an average NFL quarter=
back typically has around a 50 QBR, while a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Pro_Bowl" title=3D"Pro Bowl">Pro Bowl</a> caliber quarterback wil=
l have approximately a 75. This scale also represents a percentile of overa=
ll quarterback performances since 2006. This means that if a quarterback ha=
s a QBR of 90 their performance in that game is, on average, better than 90=
% of other quarterback performances.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Passer_rating#cite_note-13"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p><p>It is also very common for there to be significant differences betwe=
en QBR and passer rating leaders due to the additional variables and situat=
ional play context that contribute to the calculation of QBR. For example, =
in 2019, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lamar_Jackson" title=3D"L=
amar Jackson">Lamar Jackson</a> had a league leading QBR of 83.0 and earned=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NFL_Most_Valuable_Player_Award" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"NFL Most Valuable Player Award">MVP honors</a=
>. However, in terms of passer rating, Jackson (113.3) finished behind <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ryan_Tannehill" title=3D"Ryan Tannehil=
l">Ryan Tannehill</a> (117.5) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Drew_Brees" title=3D"Drew Brees">Drew Brees</a> (116.3), who finished ninth=
 and third in QBR, respectively.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"PFF_Player_Grades">PFF Play=
er Grades</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPa=
sser_rating&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: PFF P=
layer Grades"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pro_Football_Focus" title=3D"Pr=
o Football Focus">Pro Football Focus</a> (PFF) is a football website that c=
onducts in-depth analysis on NFL and NCAA games and players. Part of this a=
nalysis involves assigning each player in the NFL, as well as the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_Four_conferences" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Power Four conferences">Power Four</a> at the collegiate leve=
l, a grade that indicates their performance.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2_14-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Passer_rating#ci=
te_note-:2-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>According to PFF, the group's algorithm analyzes every play for each=
 individual player and measures the impact that said player has while on th=
e field. A player's impact is then given a grade between =E2=88=922 and +2 =
in 0.5 increments.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2_14-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Passer_rating#cite_note-:2-14"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> Each position has a scale with a unique algorithm and rules. The scale al=
so takes into account game context, so a strong play in the fourth quarter =
of a close matchup will be graded higher than one in the 2nd quarter of a b=
lowout game.
</p><p>A 0 player grade on any given play represents any position player pe=
rforming at an expected level and in a manner that neither positively nor n=
egatively impacts their team. An example of this is a running back taking a=
 carry through the correct hole and picking up three to four yards in a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Down_(gridiron_football)" title=3D"Do=
wn (gridiron football)">1st and ten</a> situation. Meanwhile, a +2 represen=
ts an incredible performance on a play that shifts the dynamic of a game in=
 favor of the player's team. Philadelphia Eagles defensive end <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brandon_Graham" title=3D"Brandon Graham">Brand=
on Graham</a>'s strip sack on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_=
Brady" title=3D"Tom Brady">Tom Brady</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_LII" title=3D"Super Bowl LII">Super Bowl LII</a> would=
 have easily been a +2 rating.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2_14-2" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Passer_rating#cite_note-:2-14"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> On the other hand, a =E2=88=922 is a play that catastrophicall=
y hinders a team's chance of winning, such as a quarterback throwing a pick=
-six in the fourth quarter of a close game. Ambiguous plays where the outco=
me is unclear on how a player impacted their team are typically given a 0.
</p><p>The sum of these plus-minuses are then converted on a 0=E2=80=93100 =
scale and produce a grade for a single game. However, a player's season gra=
de is not the average of the 17 grades a player receives each game. Instead=
, PFF credits a player's entire body of work and longevity throughout the s=
eason. It is, therefore, possible for a player to have a higher season grad=
e than any individual grade that a player received in any game he played in=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2_14-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Passer_rating#cite_note-:2-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
